know what changes happened. Did they

00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:20.240
happen together? Did they happen as a
package, were some of the features

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:24.860
evolving at different times in different
places? Those are the data that we have to

00:21:24.860 --> 00:21:28.790
come up with our ideas about why it all
happened. So when we look at something

00:21:28.790 --> 00:21:33.260
like this, we see australopiths here. They
sort of had the stocky ape shape. They're

00:21:33.260 --> 00:21:37.780
maybe living partly in the trees. And then
we have these more savanna-dwelling,

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:41.990
animals that may have been doing long
distance walking and running, using fancy

00:21:41.990 --> 00:21:47.000
pants stone tools, all kinds of things.
But in terms of the post cranial skeleton,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.860
some of the features that we think of with
this transition that fuels our adaptive

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:55.690
ideas is have to do with changes in limb
proportions, changes in lower limb joint

00:21:55.690 --> 00:22:00.840
size, changes in the shape of the torso,
changes in body size and dimorphism or

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:04.520
difference between males and females.
So what I'd like to do today is take you

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:07.990
through a little bit of the evidence we
have and there's only a little bit to talk

00:22:07.990 --> 00:22:13.270
about so I won't be up here very long, to
see first of all was australopithecus

00:22:13.270 --> 00:22:18.140
different from what we think of as Homo as
we thought. And I'm also going to talk a

00:22:18.140 --> 00:22:21.890
little bit about what we have from the
earliest part of the Homo fossil record in

00:22:21.890 --> 00:22:25.480
the way of post cranial bones that may
tell us something about what was

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:28.500
happening. So we'll start with
australopiths because that's the easy

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:32.620
part, we have more fossils. If you open up
any human evolution textbook you'll see a

00:22:32.620 --> 00:22:36.580
picture something like this where you look
at the body shape of the torso of

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:40.510
australopithecus and you see this
reconstruction. This is based on fossils

00:22:40.510 --> 00:22:44.620
done 35 or 40 years ago. There are more
fossils that have come in to change our

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:48.360
ideas a little bit. But you see, the
stocky anamode with this cone shaped rib

00:22:48.360 --> 00:22:52.390
cage. If you connect the dots there and
imagine the belly of this. Big belly, very

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:56.520
stiff and immovable and this would shape
