00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:08.530
way to look at things. We have a number of
different vertebral columns that show that

00:23:08.530 --> 00:23:12.770
the characteristic curvatures in the human
vertebral column that holds us upright

00:23:12.770 --> 00:23:16.570
were present in early australopithecus.
There are lots of vertebrae in the lower

00:23:16.570 --> 00:23:21.550
back so they can stand up fully upright.
So they're not that ape-like that way. And

00:23:21.550 --> 00:23:24.370
there are new fossils that are bringing
new bits of data and I'll show you one of

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:28.540
those bits of data. This is a skeleton
called Kadanuumu, it means big man. It's

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:33.200
an australopithecus male and he's nice and
big. And we're very excited, those of us

00:23:33.200 --> 00:23:36.620
who care about ribs are very excited
because it actually has some ribs. And you

00:23:36.620 --> 00:23:40.240
can measure the curvature of those ribs to
say something about what maybe the rib

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:44.580
cage would have been like. And you see,
apes have this cone shaped rib cage of

00:23:44.580 --> 00:23:49.210
very sort of straight ribs. Humans' curve
around, give you this more slender barrel

00:23:49.210 --> 00:23:53.920
shape rib cage. You can measure this in
Kadanuumu and you can see it's right down

00:23:53.920 --> 00:23:58.490
here with humans and gibbons who also have
this rib cage shape. Very different from

00:23:58.490 --> 00:24:02.290
something we see in great apes and data
like these are giving us the picture that

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:06.550
in fact the body shape of australopithecus
may not have been so different from our

00:24:06.550 --> 00:24:10.550
own as we had long thought.
