00:24:45.210 --> 00:24:48.920
short legs. And Trent Holiday and other
people have done similar analyses to

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:52.460
suggest that maybe the lower limbs weren't
that much shorter than australopiths,

00:24:52.460 --> 00:24:56.420
they're just littler animals. So they may
not be as big a change in limb length from

00:24:56.420 --> 00:25:00.750
australopiths to Homo as we have thought.
Another thing we've learned recently comes

00:25:00.750 --> 00:25:04.880
from the foot. An ape has a foot with not
just a grasping big toe, but the whole

00:25:04.880 --> 00:25:09.020
thing is flexible, so it can wrap around
branches and hang on in the trees. Whereas

00:25:09.020 --> 00:25:13.430
our feet are very stiff and they form a
nice propulsive lever to move us forward

00:25:13.430 --> 00:25:17.030
when we walk on the ground on two feet,
and that propulsive lever is supported by

00:25:17.030 --> 00:25:21.020
arches that go from front to back and side
to side that are built into the structure

00:25:21.020 --> 00:25:24.820
of the bones of our foot. So one we lift
our heels off the ground, they stiffen up

00:25:24.820 --> 00:25:29.560
and they let us work well. We've known for
a long time from fossil footprints that

00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:34.860
australopithecus did not have a grasping
big toe. But recently, Bill Kimble and his

00:25:34.860 --> 00:25:39.310
colleagues found this bone from the middle
