00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:52.740
little bit into life history, as I said,
we can learn a tremendous amount about

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:59.880
ourselves. And it starts out in childhood.
You have a difference in the growth and

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:05.530
development pattern that's very obvious.
For example, chimpanzees all mature by the

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:10.890
time they're about 12 years old. For
humans it takes up until your late teens,

00:39:10.890 --> 00:39:18.300
17, 18 years old. And our colleague, Barry
Bogan, has been very clear about the tempo

00:39:18.300 --> 00:39:24.930
differences that you have if you compare a
chimpanzee with a human. The chimpanzee

00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:29.720
graph there shows that you have a rapid
decline in the velocity of growth. A

00:39:29.720 --> 00:39:35.330
relatively small plateau period, that's
the juvenile period. And then another

00:39:35.330 --> 00:39:41.960
relatively rapid decline in how fast
you're growing. Humans are very different

00:39:41.960 --> 00:39:46.910
in the corner. We have that same decline
in the velocity of growth but we have a

00:39:46.910 --> 00:39:53.280
much longer plateau period where our
children are not growing very rapidly. And

00:39:53.280 --> 00:39:58.750
this is followed by the adolescent growth
spurt and then it falls off again. This

00:39:58.750 --> 00:40:04.100
pattern is very unique and it's very
important to our evolution.

00:40:04.100 --> 00:40:09.540
The last graph is from the work of Kristin
Hawkes who's here in the audience. It

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:14.150
shows you not only do you have the
difference in the pattern of the growth

00:40:14.150 --> 00:40:20.560
but we also have a very much longer
longevity or life span. Now what I find

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:25.600
fascinating particularly about the early
childhood growth is that it has a lot to

00:40:25.600 --> 00:40:30.510
do with the brain. We know that humans
have brain sizes about three times the

00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:37.870
size of a chimpanzee and that brain grows
and develops at different paces in the two

00:40:37.870 --> 00:40:45.430
species. Now in humans, as a child is
growing, a very young child with a huge

00:40:45.430 --> 00:40:52.210
head uses about 60% of the energy budget
just to support that brain size. And as we

00:40:52.210 --> 00:40:59.400
grow and our body begins to grow, the
brain growth slows down and the energy

00:40:59.400 --> 00:41:06.780
balance tips. One of our colleagues, Chris
Kozawa, has come up with I think is a

00:41:06.780 --> 00:41:13.360
brilliant look at the relationship between
this brain growth and body growth. In

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:19.410
these graphs, the red line, one for males,
the second graph for females. The red

00:41:19.410 --> 00:41:26.680
shows the energy that the brain takes as
you move from birth up through five years

00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:33.160
of age that is one of the most energy
expensive periods of brain growth in

00:41:33.160 --> 00:41:38.930
childhood because of all the mileazation
that's going on and then it drops off. The

00:41:38.930 --> 00:41:45.120
blue line is the velocity of your somatic
growth, your body growth. So basically

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:51.080
there's almost a perfect play off between
brain growth and somatic growth. And this

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:58.840
goes terribly long ways to explaining why
we have this extended period of childhood

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:03.820
that basically correlates and is a
necessary correlate in energetic terms

00:42:03.820 --> 00:42:08.480
with the growth and development of the
large human brain cells.

00:42:08.480 --> 00:42:14.660
Now we all may think this is fine and good
but it's actually not. So some of our

00:42:14.660 --> 00:42:21.150
other colleagues from Switzerland, Karin
Isler and Carel van Schaik have developed

00:42:21.150 --> 00:42:26.800
something they called the gray ceiling.
And what the importance of this is you can

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:32.490
just take so long in your growth and
development or you aren't going to be able

00:42:32.490 --> 00:42:40.510
to replace your population size. Now think
in terms of dependent childhood and if a

00:42:40.510 --> 00:42:45.890
child is dependent on a mother for five
years, six years, seven years, she's going

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:52.010
to come back into fertility. You're going
to extend that inter birth interval. You

00:42:52.010 --> 00:42:57.890
aren't going to be able to have enough
surviving children to replace your

00:42:57.890 --> 00:43:03.070
population from one generation to another
generation. Okay, this is what they call

00:43:03.070 --> 00:43:09.360
the gray ceiling. And if you look at the
graph here, there is a lot of primates.

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:15.350
The red dots are the apes with the
increasing brain size. And what this shows

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:21.180
is that with some of our apes like the
orangutans, the gorillas and all, what

00:43:21.180 --> 00:43:25.660
they're arguing is they're hitting the
gray ceiling and the only way to avoid

00:43:25.660 --> 00:43:33.370
that gray ceiling is to somehow increase
your reproductive output. Now if we go

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:38.990
back to that same little chart I chose
earlier, at the bottom is the period of

00:43:38.990 --> 00:43:44.740
infancy. And in chimpanzees, infants are
dependent on their mother, they're still

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:48.870
nursing. They are four to four and a half
years old before they're weaned. In

00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:54.580
humans, it's of course very much shorter
and this particular graph shows about two

00:43:54.580 --> 00:44:01.460
years, it varies. But what the take home
message of this is is you can have twice

00:44:01.460 --> 00:44:06.070
as many kids if you shorten that period of
infancy.

00:44:06.070 --> 00:44:10.730
And if you then shorten your interval
between birth. Now again you may think

00:44:10.730 --> 00:44:16.050
this is fine, this is a good trick, we've
all developed it, but it has tremendous

00:44:16.050 --> 00:44:21.040
problems. And I've got this picture
hanging in my office and whenever I think

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:28.050
I'm having a hard day I think of her.
Because what you have once you start to

00:44:28.050 --> 00:44:36.760
double up this is you have a woman who may
be pregnant. The infant that she's

00:44:36.760 --> 00:44:43.680
probably in the last stage of nursing and
a dependent kid. And she has to get the

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:49.670
food to support her own large body weight,
her own large brain size, and to provide

00:44:49.670 --> 00:44:56.170
all of the calories for the kids she's
nursing. She has to provide the food for

00:44:56.170 --> 00:45:01.750
the young infant. Now this is very
different from what we see in the

00:45:01.750 --> 00:45:09.020
chimpanzees or other apes where mothers
focus on one infant. And once the infant

00:45:09.020 --> 00:45:14.820
has stopped nursing they will gather their
own food. There's very little energetic

00:45:14.820 --> 00:45:20.820
involvement with the mother. Now this is a
huge paradox and this is where the

00:45:20.820 --> 00:45:26.550
evolution of sharing and cooperation comes
in. And of course this is where we have

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:33.410
the grandmother hypothesis and the
argument that a lot of the extra resources

00:45:33.410 --> 00:45:39.220
for the grandkids come from the
grandmother by provisioning the mother and

00:45:39.220 --> 00:45:45.160
the kids. Now there's a number of other
arguments also that involved greater

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:52.430
cooperation among all individuals in the
society, males as well as sibling care and

00:45:52.430 --> 00:45:58.180
sibling cooperation. The take home message
is that once you begin to develop a large

00:45:58.180 --> 00:46:02.700
brain size, you have growth and
development implications.

00:46:02.700 --> 00:46:06.710
And these growth and development
implications have implications for the

00:46:06.710 --> 00:46:11.950
evolution of what we would recognize as a
human type of cooperative social

00:46:11.950 --> 00:46:18.160
organization. Okay, the big question is,
can we tell when this all happened in

00:46:18.160 --> 00:46:23.280
human evolution? And we'd like to think,
oh, this is a characteristic of the root

00:46:23.280 --> 00:46:28.300
of the genus Homo, that's a hypothesis.
Now if we go back to the evolutionary

00:46:28.300 --> 00:46:34.210
tree, we have one way into this in terms
of cooperation. And if we go back to the

00:46:34.210 --> 00:46:39.760
gray ceiling and I know Burden isn't going
to like my brain size against a million

00:46:39.760 --> 00:46:46.640
year graph. But if we put the gray ceiling
onto this and again what Isler and van

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:53.700
Schaik argue is that gray ceiling is about
700 milliliters. Now of course there is,

00:46:53.700 --> 00:46:58.820
you know, big ranges of variation around
this, but what's interesting about this is

00:46:58.820 --> 00:47:07.220
this just about divides our Homo erectus
from the earlier hominids. And if we put

00:47:07.220 --> 00:47:12.680
it on our evolutionary tree here, it comes
at this very interesting time between two

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:18.970
million and one million years ago where
you have a proliferation of hominids, a

00:47:18.970 --> 00:47:26.890
variety of different species, and you have
this big variation in the brain sizes that

00:47:26.890 --> 00:47:31.990
we have. Now as we've also heard, this
time period correlates with the radical

00:47:31.990 --> 00:47:37.300
change in human adaptation. And
particularly in evidence for the

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:43.670
precedence of animal based tissues in the
diet, it also correlates again with our

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:49.470
Turkana boy here and this general time
period where you have the evolution of

00:47:49.470 --> 00:47:55.230
what we call Homo erectus. Now what's
interesting about this also is it also

00:47:55.230 --> 00:48:01.000
correlates with the time period where
hominids begin to move out of Africa.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:06.900
So our question here is how much does this
cooperative behavior that we can infer

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:12.580
from the brain size and we can refer from
the life history really affect the

00:48:12.580 --> 00:48:19.360
hominid's ability to adapt to a variety of
different habitats not only in Africa but

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:25.020
also throughout the world? Now the only
direct evidence we have for any type of

00:48:25.020 --> 00:48:32.620
cooperation comes from the side of Dmanisi
and our friend here with no teeth. And I'm

00:48:32.620 --> 00:48:39.240
sure it feels very familiar with the
argument that this individual must have

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:45.330
whatever you want to argue, been taken
care of. The message from this is we don't

00:48:45.330 --> 00:48:50.080
really know how to recognize this
cooperation in the fossil record. It would

00:48:50.080 --> 00:48:57.120
be very nice if we could. Now if we come
back to the fossils, is there any way from

00:48:57.120 --> 00:49:03.400
the fossils we could tell what their tempo
of growth is? And in this case, one of our

00:49:03.400 --> 00:49:08.650
colleagues, Chris Dean, has been working
on how to infer growth and development

00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:14.240
from the formation of the teeth. I've been
very impressed by some recent work by

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:19.130
Chris and his colleague, Helen Livesidge
in London. Not on teeth this time in

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:25.990
particular, but on body size because what
Chris has done is sort of bracketed the

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:31.650
age of our Turkana boy at death to
somewhere between seven and eight years

00:49:31.650 --> 00:49:38.340
old. Now what these graph show were really
startling to me because the green one is

00:49:38.340 --> 00:49:45.330
stature. And the histogram is the stature
