00:49:45.330 --> 00:49:53.090
7 and 10 years old. The red line there is
the estimate for the Turkana boy. It's way

00:49:53.090 --> 00:49:59.680
in excess of the stature that you would
expect. The blue is body mass or body

00:49:59.680 --> 00:50:05.670
weight. Again way outside of what you
would expect in modern human kids.

00:50:05.670 --> 00:50:11.080
Now what does this tell you about the
growth and development of the Turkana boy?

00:50:11.080 --> 00:50:17.910
If we go back to Barry Bogan's figures,
what it's telling you is that the Turkana

00:50:17.910 --> 00:50:28.600
boy was growing on a trend very much more
similar to the apes than to modern humans.

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:35.390
And if you look on the chart, in fact just
above age there on the chimp chart is

00:50:35.390 --> 00:50:42.090
eight years old. And you've come out of
that plateau of slow growth velocity, the

00:50:42.090 --> 00:50:47.970
individual would be then growing towards
his adult weight. In humans, it would be

00:50:47.970 --> 00:50:54.550
still well within that plateau before that
growth explosion, that's the adolescent

00:50:54.550 --> 00:51:02.280
growth spurt. Now this, to me, is very
convincing evidence that the Turkana boy

00:51:02.280 --> 00:51:07.930
was not growing and developing on the
human pattern. Now what that would mean is

00:51:07.930 --> 00:51:12.990
that it would reach maturity much more
rapidly than if it was growing on the

00:51:12.990 --> 00:51:20.720
modern human sort of tempo and mode. Now
is there anything more we can tell? Your

00:51:20.720 --> 00:51:27.680
eruption of teeth tends to still also
measure how long your growth period is.

00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:32.810
And what's become very clear recently is
there's a tremendous amount of overlap not

00:51:32.810 --> 00:51:40.010
only between living human tooth eruption
and tooth formation patterns and apes, but

00:51:40.010 --> 00:51:44.810
also overlap in the fossil hominids. And
when it comes down to it, if you're

00:51:44.810 --> 00:51:49.580
looking at tooth formation, your best
tooth in terms of distinguishing us

00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:55.180
between the chimps and humans is your
third molar. But again the take home

00:51:55.180 --> 00:52:03.260
message from this comes in the bottom
graph. And the blue line there is the

00:52:03.260 --> 00:52:10.770
tooth development for your second premolar
and that's in the chimps, the red one is

00:52:10.770 --> 00:52:14.610
in humans.
The vertical lines are your early Homo

00:52:14.610 --> 00:52:21.410
fossils. The green one is the Turkana boy.
And although the teeth are developing at

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:25.120
the very, very fast end of modern humans
and there's a tremendous amount of

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:32.040
variation, it's squarely within the ape
pattern as well. And if we're going to

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:39.400
argue about what the life history patterns
of some of these early Homo are, basically

00:52:39.400 --> 00:52:44.250
we're talking about a much more ape-like
growth and development pattern than a

00:52:44.250 --> 00:52:49.910
human-like growth and development pattern.
Okay, the next questions comes in is when

00:52:49.910 --> 00:52:57.170
did we start to grow and develop as
humans? And the first indication is with

00:52:57.170 --> 00:53:04.360
Homo antecessor which is about a million,
not .9 million years old. The teeth are

00:53:04.360 --> 00:53:09.160
still developing more rapidly than ours,
meaning they're developing more rapidly.

00:53:09.160 --> 00:53:14.940
But the argument is made that the first
ones that are closer to modern humans than

00:53:14.940 --> 00:53:20.460
to the early Homo, the early
australopithecine pattern. And then as we

00:53:20.460 --> 00:53:27.930
move up to the top at about a 160,000
years ago at the Moroccan side of Jebel

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:33.050
Irhoud and this is some of some John Jack
Hublin's and his group right there in the

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:39.940
fourth row, where you have a very modern
human growth and development pattern. Now

00:53:39.940 --> 00:53:50.290
what I want to do is sort of finish with
what is probably everybody's favorite

00:53:50.290 --> 00:53:55.510
fossil and that's the neanderthals. And
they're a long way up the record from what

00:53:55.510 --> 00:54:00.140
we're talking about in the evolution of
the genus Homo. But I think the lessons we

00:54:00.140 --> 00:54:05.550
can learn from the neanderthal growth and
development, we can usefully bring down

00:54:05.550 --> 00:54:10.070
the record and apply to some of the
australopithecines.

00:54:10.070 --> 00:54:16.540
Now neanderthals of course are the
alternatives to modern humans. They have

00:54:16.540 --> 00:54:24.480
brain sizes that overlap with ours. They
are in the blue series of Xes there. They

00:54:24.480 --> 00:54:30.980
lived in Europe during the last ice age
while anatomically modern humans were

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:37.810
evolving elsewhere in Africa. What, again,
another piece of evidence that struck me

00:54:37.810 --> 00:54:42.820
that comes out of Martin Gonzales and some
of his colleagues' work from Spain is the

00:54:42.820 --> 00:54:49.510
growth and development of the little
neanderthal kids. So the blue lines here

00:54:49.510 --> 00:54:56.480
are your growth from not years, up to 70
months. The horizontal lines are the

00:54:56.480 --> 00:55:03.630
equivalently aged neanderthals in relation
to that modern human growth pattern. So

00:55:03.630 --> 00:55:09.760
here you can say the little neanderthals
are basically plateauing much earlier than

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:15.670
you would see in the human growth curve.
Now think about being a neanderthal. I'm

00:55:15.670 --> 00:55:21.880
often happy I wasn't born a neanderthal
because, you know, what the authors are

00:55:21.880 --> 00:55:27.780
arguing here is not only do they have the
energetic stress of growing and developing

00:55:27.780 --> 00:55:31.950
that large human-like brain size, they
also have a serious thermoregulatory

00:55:31.950 --> 00:55:39.370
problem. Because in fact with Steve
Churchlin I've done some modeling on the

00:55:39.370 --> 00:55:43.970
energetic requirements in neanderthals and
it's about the same as to say somebody

00:55:43.970 --> 00:55:50.880
riding the Tour de France in the Alps.
It's about 500 kilocalories a day. And you

00:55:50.880 --> 00:55:55.800
think of these poor little neanderthals
trying to support that brain and also keep

00:55:55.800 --> 00:56:02.080
warm. Now there is a second piece also
that comes from other research.

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:10.540
This is from Smith et al in 2010. And the
green lines here are your expected and

00:56:10.540 --> 00:56:17.600
predicted ages for human teeth and the
blue lines are the neanderthals. The take

00:56:17.600 --> 00:56:24.050
home message is their teeth are developing
more rapidly so they have a more

00:56:24.050 --> 00:56:32.030
attenuated growth and development process.
Now coming back to this and where you

00:56:32.030 --> 00:56:36.520
would expect to say a modern human
populations to have more rapid growth and

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:42.600
development. It's in situations where you
have a higher mortality rate. Now think

00:56:42.600 --> 00:56:47.500
about these poor neanderthals, they have a
very high mortality rate, every three

00:56:47.500 --> 00:56:54.190
calistosis. It's the same as rodeo riders
in the southwest. And you have these poor

00:56:54.190 --> 00:57:01.120
little stressed neanderthals with a
shorter body size. Now if we come back to

00:57:01.120 --> 00:57:08.410
all of our, you know, fossil species, our
australopithecines and early Homo, living

00:57:08.410 --> 00:57:14.740
